04489nam a22005655i 9780226922362DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20132012ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2012019393  a9780226922362  a(DE-B1597)524278  a(OCoLC)820172862  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPR447b.S58 2013 4aPR447b.S58 2013 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a820.9/145223  aHL 1101qBVB2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/50382:1 aSimpson, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRomanticism and the Question of the Stranger /cDavid Simpson. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2013] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: After 9/11: The Ubiquity of Others -- t1. Theorizing Strangers: A Very Long Romanticism -- t2. Hearth and Home: Coleridge, De Quincey, Austen -- t3. Friends and Enemies in Walter Scott’s Crusader Novels -- t4. Small Print and Wide Horizons -- t5. Strange Words: The Call to Translation -- t6. Hands across the Ocean: Slavery and Sociability -- t7. Strange Women -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn our post-9/11 world, the figure of the stranger—the foreigner, the enemy, the unknown visitor—carries a particular urgency, and the force of language used to describe those who are “different” has become particularly strong. But arguments about the stranger are not unique to our time. In Romanticism and the Question of the Stranger, David Simpson locates the figure of the stranger and the rhetoric of strangeness in romanticism and places them in a tradition that extends from antiquity to today. Simpson shows that debates about strangers loomed large in the French Republic of the 1790s, resulting in heated discourse that weighed who was to be welcomed and who was to be proscribed as dangerous. Placing this debate in the context of classical, biblical, and other later writings, he identifies a persistent difficulty in controlling the play between the despised and the desired. He examines the stranger as found in the works of Coleridge, Austen, Scott, and Southey, as well as in depictions of the betrayals of hospitality in the literature of slavery and exploration—as in Mungo Park's Travels and Stedman's Narrative—and portrayals of strange women in de Staël, Rousseau, and Burney. Contributing to a rich strain of thinking about the stranger that includes interventions by Ricoeur and Derrida, Romanticism and the Question of the Stranger reveals the complex history of encounters with alien figures and our continued struggles with romantic concerns about the unknown.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aOther (Philosophy) in literature. 0aRomanticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aromanticism, romantics, stranger, unknown, foreigner, foreign, enemy, visitor, difference, different, strangeness, narrative, tradition, danger, dangerous, classical, bible, biblical, philosophy, literature, literary, criticism, walter scott, slavery, gender, sociability, jane austen, samuel taylor coleridge, robert southey, sublime, imagination, nature, melancholy, subjectivity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022692235540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226922362423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226922362/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles